Pag. 68. Vol. 3. Some of the ableſt of the Peripatetick School (not without countenance from Ariſtotle himſelf, in the 5th Chapter of his 3d Book 
                  〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
               ) hold, That beſides the Native Inherent Light of the Intellect (which is eſſential to it, as it is a Faculty made to apprehend, and take in its Object after a ſpiritual way) there is alſo another Light in the Nature of a Medium, bearning in upon it by a continual efflux and emanation from the Great Fountain of Light, and irradiating this intellectual Faculty, together with Species and Repreſentations of things imprinted thereupon. According to which Doctrin, it ſeems, with great reaſon, to follow; That whatſoever interpoſes between the Mind, and thoſe irradiations from God (as all Sin more or leſs certainly does) muſt needs hinder the entrance and admiſſion of them into the Mind, and then darkneſs muſt by neceſſary conſequence enſue, as being nothing elſe but the abſence or privation of Light.
